name: NPR
text:
The scope of the suspected Russian hack into SolarWinds is still being uncovered. The company provided IT management services to at least 17,000 customers, including private firms and the U.S. government.
https://t.co/aV9MARj73i

name: NPR
text:
Congress has approved a 2-day temporary funding bill to avoid a government shutdown — just hours before the midnight deadline. Talks on a COVID-19 stimulus deal remain stalled.
https://t.co/OvlplAKlsp

name: NPR
text:
A new trove of previously undisclosed federal data reveals that nearly 900 of 938 U.S. metro areas and more than 2,000 of 3,270 counties qualify as "sustained hotspots" for COVID-19.
https://t.co/KFmGZBQYRP

name: NPR
text:
Stanford Medicine apologized for a plan that had just 7 of more than 1,300 residents getting a vaccine in the first round of doses. An algorithm assigned some senior faculty to get shots before front-line workers who treat COVID-19 patients.
https://t.co/41jH34GuHy

name: NPR
text: Nearly 350 Nigerian schoolboys have safely walked free after Boko Haram kidnapped them from their school last Friday. The attack recalled the group's 2014 abduction of 276 schoolgirls — nearly half of whom appear to remain in captivity. https://t.co/nCfNc7PVQt

name: NPR
text:
President Trump has signed the 2-day stopgap bill to avoid a shutdown. Negotiations will continue over the weekend.
https://t.co/7mEUqCIWOZ

name: NPR
text:
The U.S. State Department is shutting down its consulate in Vladivostok, Russia, and suspending operations at one in Yekaterinburg, officials confirmed on Friday.
https://t.co/GIFP8l4duo

name: NPR
text: It's a bad day for Johnny Silverhand: Sony is offering a full refund for anyone who purchased "Cyberpunk 2077" from its PlayStation store. The launch of the highly anticipated open world game has been plagued by bugs. https://t.co/xqiWlXqSks

name: NPR
text: A lot of self-improvement efforts were derailed by *gestures at everything* in 2020. How are you setting goals for the coming year? Click through and let us know. https://t.co/THRkyJLoQ7

name: NPR
text:
Virginia and Maryland will send thousands of extra vaccine doses out of their own supply to D.C., which received 6,825 doses — enough to cover less than a tenth of the city's health workers.
https://t.co/1oWubYRzaO

name: NPR
text:
As foreign forces withdraw, the Taliban have waged violent attacks on Afghan government forces across the country. There are signs the government is losing control over Kabul.

Many graduates now want to leave: "At least to have security and to be alive." https://t.co/OMb3NwiyBB

name: NPR
text: The radio industry has been hit hard by the pandemic, with ratings falling as much as 50% at first. Some stations figured Christmas tunes were worth a shot, and started spinning them as early as the middle of summer. https://t.co/ELohdV36lN

name: NPR
text: NPR’s Book Concierge has the largest batch of recommendations we’ve ever compiled – here are 380+ of our favorite 2020 titles. (And stick around to browse nearly 2,500 books from the last eight years.) https://t.co/USVoXhQRC4

name: NPR
text: COVID-19 is now the No. 1 cause of death in Peru, Brazil, Chile, Ecuador and Panama. https://t.co/KAljNGiMRr

name: NPR
text:
2020 is in a dead-heat tie for the hottest year on record. We asked scientists what lessons can be learned from another hot year.
https://t.co/OTwSwyXHH8

name: NPR
text:
Las alarmas, las bocinas, los zumbidos son ruidos para la mayoría. Para Juan Pablo, son música. Para él, sus oídos son lo que sus ojos no alcanzan a ver. 

Escuchen su historia en @radioambulante, nuestro podcast en español. https://t.co/GZy00cigWS

name: NPR
text: President Trump often takes credit for "unleashing America's scientific genius" in pursuit of a coronavirus vaccine. But immigrants have been involved in every facet of that effort, and people in the industry say U.S. genius depends on global talent. https://t.co/zr0Auh9tqq

name: NPR
text: Flood insurance rates have been soaring in recent years, forcing some people out of their homes. Cities can earn their residents a discount through mitigation work and a federal program, but only a few communities are taking full advantage. https://t.co/IveOHClksp

name: NPR
text: "I'm just worrying as to whether everything I've built, like everything I've worked for my entire life, is going to crumble." In Massachusetts, one in four restaurants has already gone out of business, and the rest are barely hanging on. https://t.co/2SW1Jg6rzd

name: NPR
text:
MARLEY: I am here to-day to warn you, that you have yet a chance and hope! You will be haunted by Three Spirits ... each named Hanson. Also Amy Grant and Sharon Jones and others! 
(Through door stage left enter GHOSTS OF TINY DESK PAST)
https://t.co/VjrS0pAFH7

name: NPR
text: Kwanza Hall was elected to Congress this year, but there's a catch -- he only gets to serve for one month, completing the term of the late Rep. John Lewis. He tells @gpbnews  about jumping into the job of congressman with the clock already ticking. https://t.co/YJ3PSxCYlZ
